## 2. Core Performance Metrics

### 2.1 Win Rate by Sentiment

| Sentiment | Win Rate | vs. Overall (41.1%) |
|---|---|---|
| Extreme Fear | 37.1% | −4.0 pp |
| Fear | 42.1% | +1.0 pp |
| Neutral | 39.7% | −1.4 pp |
| Greed | 38.5% | −2.6 pp |
| **Extreme Greed** | **46.5%** | **+5.4 pp** |

**Key takeaway:** Extreme Greed produces a win rate 9.4 percentage points higher than Extreme Fear. The market's most euphoric periods are — counterintuitively — the most reliably profitable for these traders.

### 2.2 Average PnL per Trade

| Sentiment | Avg PnL | Median PnL |
|---|---|---|
| Extreme Fear | $34.54 | $0.00 |
| Fear | $54.29 | $0.00 |
| Neutral | $35.43 | $0.00 |
| Greed | $42.74 | $0.00 |
| **Extreme Greed** | **$67.89** | **$0.00** |

The universal $0.00 median confirms the dataset is heavily skewed — most trades result in zero or near-zero PnL (flat closes, partial fills, or very small positions). The mean is driven by a relatively small number of large winning trades.

### 2.3 Total PnL by Sentiment

| Sentiment | Total PnL | Share of Total |
|---|---|---|
| Fear | $3,357,155 | 32.6% |
| Extreme Greed | $2,715,171 | 26.4% |
| Greed | $2,150,129 | 20.9% |
| Neutral | $1,335,393 | 13.0% |
| Extreme Fear | $739,110 | 7.2% |

Fear generates the most total PnL in absolute terms — not because of superior per-trade quality, but because it contains the most trades (29.3% of volume). Extreme Greed punches well above its weight: 18.9% of trades but 26.4% of total PnL.

